  "description": "¶Propositions as types In Agda, there is no separate Prop sort — propositions are ordinary types in Set. A proof of proposition P is a term of type P. The logical connectives are defined as data types:\n-- Conjunction record _×_ (A B : Set) : Set where constructor _,_ field fst : A ; snd : B -- Disjunction data _⊎_ (A B : Set) : Set where inj₁ : A → A ⊎ B inj₂ : B → A ⊎ B -- Negation ¬_ : Set → Set ¬ A = A → ⊥ -- where ⊥ is the empty type -- Existential -- Σ type (see previous lesson) -- Universal: dependent function type (x : A) → P x Because Agda is intuitionistic, excluded middle is not available by default. A proof of A ⊎ B must supply a proof of A or a proof of B — you cannot argue \u0026ldquo;suppose neither, derive a contradiction.\u0026rdquo;\n",
